The Sola Valley and the Monte Alban State: A Study of 'Zapotec Imperial Expansion. ANDREW K. BALKAN­SKY. Museum of Anthropology, University of Michi­gan Memoir No. 36, Ann Arbor, 2002. xvi +126 pp., figures, tables, appendices, bibliography. $25.00 (paper). 
Reviewed by Andrew Workinger, University of Ten­nessee, Chattanooga 
Sola is a small, semi-arid valley just south of the well­documented Valley of Oaxaca in Mexico. The latter is home to Monte Alban, regional capital of the Zapotec state. Driving Balkansky's survey was the desire to gauge the effects of a possible Zapotec expansion into the Sola Valley during the Late/Terminal Formative (300 B.C.-A.D. 200). First suggested some 25 years ago, the question of Zapotec colonization and/or con­quest of various regions in Oaxaca has proven to be one of the dominant issues in Oaxacan archaeology. 
Balkansky follows his introduction with a justifica­tion of why archaeological surveys continue to be rel­evant in Oaxaca, perhaps the most heavily surveyed region of Mesoamerica. The macroregional perspective is understandably emphasized and Balkansky places his work in the Sola Valley with surveys undertaken by his highland colleagues. While including in these ranks settlement pattern projects in the Valley of Oaxaca, Ejutla, the Cuicatlan Canada, and the Nochixtlan Val­ley, coastal surveys of the southern Isthmus of Tehuan­tepec and the Lower Rio Verde Valley are ignored, perhaps because they fail to support the hypothesis of Zapotec expansion. 
Chapter 3 presents the Formative period survey data from Sola, including the valley's first site dating to Period Ia (500-300 B.C.). The Late Formative (Period le; 300-200 B.C.) was marked by a large influx of peo­ple, evidence Balkansky believes of strategic Zapotec resettlement along an expanding political frontier. These early sites are positioned in the piedmont, an indi­cation that a concern for defense outweighed direct access to Sola's most arable lands. 
Why expand into the Sola Valley? Balkansky answers this question by arguing that the Zapotec were concerned not with tribute, but with establishing and maintaining a trade route to the coast via the Sola Val­ley. The Pacific coast of Oaxaca would have been a tempting source of exotic goods for the emergent Zapotec elite. 
An alternative interpretation, suggested by Feinman and Nicholas to explain similar settlement patterns found in the Ejutla Valley immediately to the east of Sola, is that the relationship between Monte Alban and these secondary valleys was one of competition rather than incorporation ( 1990, Latin American Antiquity 1:216-46). Low population densities and the approxi­mately even size and spacing of sites in the southern arm of the Valley of Oaxaca would support this. 
If not in the Late Formative, Balkansky argues that the Sola Valley was fully incorporated into the Zapotec state by the Terminal Formative (Period II). Concen­tration of settlement in a regional center, he argues, would have allowed the imperial administrators better control. And, now that the boundary of the Zapotec "empire" had passed south of Sola, there was no longer the need for the defensible terraced piedmont sites seen earlier. 
There may not have been the need, but settlement remained almost entirely up off the alluvium in the Sola Valley. The survey data reveal that population dropped by more than 45% from the Late Formative and that the ceramics varied from standard Valley of Oaxaca diagnostics. Given the distance between the two, it is unlikely that the Sola inhabitants were pro­viding tribute in the form of staple foods back to the Zapotec capital. Taken together, the data suggest that Sola was not fully integrated into the Monte Alban state, but instead was administered from the regional capital (site S39). The virtual abandonment of the southern arm of the Valley of Oaxaca indicates that not even that subregion had managed a hierarchical network by the Terminal Formative. 
