The Early Classic Period Illa, described in Chapter 4, is marked by a new regional center, Los Chilillos. This site was apparently situated to monitor the com­ings and goings of the Sola Valley. A new wave of immi­grants entered the valley, echoing population trends witnessed in the southern Valley of Oaxaca and the neighboring Ejutla Valley. Contiguous settlement between these three areas is the best evidence yet for political integration. Balkansky believes that the Zapotec frontier was once again positioned in Sola in the Early Classic and that the rise in population may have been the result of Zapotec settlers following the frontier as it shrank back towards the Valley of Oaxaca. 
The succeeding Late Classic period cannot be dif­ferentiated from the Early Postclassic period on the basis of surface ceramic collections. This is unfortu­nate because the combined period, Period Illb-IV, encompasses both the zenith and the decline of Monte 
Alban. The Classic/Postclassic transition has proved to be a major hurdle throughout the highlands of Oaxaca. 
Period Illb-IV brought with it significant disruption to the Sola Valley. It was then controlled by four or five competing centers. These centers are characterized by groupings of three or four mounds surrounding a plaza, as well as by ballcourts and associated carved stones. The more than 40 carved stones found by Balkansky and others in the Sola Valley make it a remarkable repository of Zapotec art and three of the stones are dis­cussed in their greater regional context by Joyce Mar­cus in Chapter 7. Marcus pegs the spread of Zapotec writing styles outside of the Valley of Oaxaca (such as those found in Sola) to the expansion of the Zapotec empire in the Late/Terminal Formative. This leaves the argued Late/Terminal Formative colonization of Sola unsupported, however, as she dates the monuments no earlier than the Late Classic period. 
Balkansky believes that the proliferation of Late Classic carved stones in the Sola Valley was the prod­uct of competing local elites jockeying for power in the vacuum left behind by MonteAlban's "disengagement" from the valley. This development mirrors what was happening further north in the Valley of Oaxaca as regional centers like Jalieza, Lambityeco, and Macuil­xochitl grabbed power from the declining Monte Alban and elite families became more dependent on self pro­motion than state-sponsored propaganda. 
Importantly, while Monte Alban was suffering from a major loss in population and monumental construc­tion, Balkansky points out that the Sola Valley was thriving. "If we are to going to understand the collapse of regional states and the transition to the Postclassic," he writes, "we must separate individual site histories ... from our notions of regional and macroregional polit­ical structure" (p. 67). 
The competing factions seen in the Late Classic/Early Postclassic presage what was to follow in the Late Postclassic Period V. Although it was first assumed that the small kingdoms called cacicazgos found in Late Postclassic Oaxaca were the product of migrating Mixtecs, archaeologists including Balkansky have provided ample evidence for local development along the fringes of the Classic period Monte Alban state. 
In the Sola Valley, Period V is characterized by a five-tiered settlement hierarchy dominated by two caci­cazgos, one on either side of the valley. This period was also marked by the valley's greatest number of sites and its highest population, the majority of whom were liv­ing in defensible high mountain sites. Based on surface collections, Balkansky was able to suggest connections between the Mixtecs and the cacicazgo in western Sola. Relatively higher numbers of Mixteca-Puebla poly­chrome, Red-on-Cream and Graphite-on-Orange ceramics suggest the tie. Other distinctions between the two cacicazgos, including the preponderance of green obsidian at the western one and its scarcity at the other, and the different decorative styles found in locally produced graywares, indicate sharply separate eco­nomic spheres. 
The difference between Balkansky's work in the Sola Valley and other projects that have sought to clar­ify the nature of a possible imperial expansion of the Late/Terminal Formative Monte Alban state is that it encompasses only survey. To make claims of Zapotec colonization as Balkansky does, requires support from excavations, particularly the material consequences left behind by imperial governors (e.g., prestige items, architecture, and mortuary traditions) and by supply­ing the Zapotec capital with goods traded up from the coast. 
